request.description:
Some payment methods like iDEAL, and some 3D Secure flows will redirect the shopper back to your website. When the shopper comes back to your website, show them the payment result, based on the result code. To get the resultCode, you need to create an instance of AdyenCheckout after the redirect, as described below.

The shopper comes back to the returnUrl specified when [creating the payment session](https://api-docs.clock-software.com/#ac1900ad-7128-4789-935d-a946af115e02). The returnUrl has query parameters appended to it, which you need to handle the redirect:

- sessionId: the unique identifier for the shopper's payment session.
- redirectResult: details you need to submit to handle the redirect.
If the shopper doesn't return to you website, you don't get a redirectResult. You don't need to do anything to handle the redirect in this case.
```
// The return URL has query parameters related to the payment session.
https://your-company.com/?sessionId=CSD9CAC34EBAE225DD&redirectResult=X6XtfGC3!Y...
```

Extract the values from the query string parameters and create a function which handles the redirect result. The function needs to:

- Create an instance of Drop-in using the **sessionId** value you extracted. <br>**!!!PLEASE NOTE: You don't need to use Clock PMS API to generate new session details. You need to reinitialize the Drop-in configuration with the existing session, use only the sessionId query parameter added to your returnUrl**
- Submit the **redirectResult** value you extracted from the **returnUrl**.

```
// Function to parse URL parameters
function getURLParameter(name) {
    return decodeURIComponent((new RegExp('[?|&]' + name + '=' + '([^&;]+?)(&|#|;|$)').exec(location.search) || [null, ''])[1].replace(/\+/g, '%20')) || null;
}
// Create an instance of AdyenCheckout to handle the shopper returning to your website.
// Configure the instance with the sessionId you extracted from the returnUrl.
async function initializeCheckout() {
    const sessionId = getURLParameter('sessionId');
    const redirectResult = getURLParameter('redirectResult');

    const configuration = {
        session: {
            id: sessionId,
        },
        // other configuration options...
    };

    try {
        const checkout = await AdyenCheckout(configuration);

        if (redirectResult) {
            checkout.submitDetails({details: {redirectResult}});
        }
        // Proceed with further actions, e.g., mount the Drop-in
    } catch (error) {
        console.error("Error initializing Adyen Checkout:", error);
    }
}

// Execute the checkout initialization
initializeCheckout();
```
If the shopper doesn't return to your website, don't call submitDetails, because the result doesn't change when you attempt the request.

After you submit the **redirectResult** value, Drop-in calls the **onPaymentCompleted(result, component)** event. Use the result code in **result.resultCode** to inform the shopper.

The onError event returns an object which contains details about the error:

|Error field|Description|
| ----------- | ----------- |
|**error.name**	|The type of error. Use the values it returns to configure localized error messages for your shoppers: <br>  - **NETWORK_ERROR**: a call that Drop-in made to the server has failed, for example because of a timeout, or if there is missing information in the request. Ask the shopper to try again. <br> - **CANCEL**: the shopper cancelled the payment. Only applies for payment methods that allow explicit cancellation in the UI, for example Apple Pay or PayPal. <br> - **IMPLEMENTATION_ERROR**: the method or parameter is incorrect or not supported. <br> - **ERROR**: generic catch-all error. Tell the shopper something went wrong and ask them to try paying again, maybe with a different payment method.|
|**error.message**|Gives more information for each type of error. The message is technical so you shouldn't show it to your shoppers. **For error.name: NETWORK_ERROR**, the information in the message field depends on the environment:<br> - **test**: you get a message with a generic error code to help you troubleshoot.<br> - **live**: the message from the response.|
|**component**|The name of the variable where you created the instance of Drop-in, for example **dropinComponent**.|

The error object may contain additional fields inherited from the [Error() constructor.](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Error/Error)
```
{
    onError: (error, component) => {
        console.error(error.name, error.message, component);
    }
}
```

item.description:
### Proper Accounting Data Synchronization is very important for the Hospitality Industry

In the dynamic world of hospitality, ensuring accurate and efficient financial management is crucial for the success of any hotel or accommodation business. One of the key components in achieving this is the proper synchronization of accounting data between Clock PMS+ and your financial system. The below explores the critical aspects of accounting data sync, focusing on the configuration of the PMS system and the collection of data via the PMS system API.

- **Configuration of the PMS System:**

    - **Revenue Accounting Code/s Configuration.** The account codes in Clock PMS+ are defined as new field/s for the charge templates.

        - Navigate to menu **Settings -> All Settings -> Charge Custom Fields >** and create the necessary Revenue accounting code field/s with **Type: string.** Once the Revenue accounting code field/s are created you can start defining the account codes for the list of charge templates.

        - Navigate to menu **Settings -> All Settings -> Charge Templates** and Edit each charge template and fill in the respective account codes. **Note**: Keep in mind the _**datev_account**_ _field needs to be filled in before posting charges to booking/folios. However, if you already have charges created you can still update their Datev account values using the_ _**Charge Custom Field Check Report.**_

    - **Payment Accounting Codes Configuration**. Navigate to menu **Settings -> All Settings -> General ledger accounts,** review the existing configurations and create new ones specifying the attributes on the screen. _**Note**_ _: The first match the system finds will assign the payment code. For example, if code 123 is configured for_ _**Payment type = Bank**_ _and code 456 is configured for the_ _**combination Payment type = Bank and Payment subtype = National Bank**_ _the system will find the first match and the code will be 123. However, you can use the Sort order (ascending) to configure how the code configuration would apply and if the code 123 has Sort order = 2 and 456 with Sort Order = 1 the latter will match first and 123 will be the default one for the bank payments. Unlike the Revenue accounting code, the change to the General ledger account code will immediately affect the General ledger account of the payments._

- **Accounting Data Sync.** When syncing data between Clock PMS+ and your financial system, several common data streams are typically involved to ensure accurate and efficient integration. Here are the most common data streams

    - **Revenue**. [<b>charges_log</b>&nbsp;](https://api-docs.clock-software.com/#f45f78a9-d0f1-4d13-b9fc-39f3514bc92e)  endpoint exposes detailed information for all charges for a given revenue date together with their taxes. **Please note:** The revenue corrections and voids are exposed as negative or reverse charges. ;

    - **Payments**. [<b>credit_item_logs</b>&nbsp;](https://api-docs.clock-software.com/#bd93bb0c-b3bb-4e4e-b158-abd8a7c391b6)  endpoint exposes detailed information for all payments collected/refunded for a given revenue date. The refunds are exposed as negative payments;

    - **Advanced payments and deposits**. [<b>Here</b>](https://academy.clock-software.com/en/support/solutions/folders/9000197699) you can find more information about deposits, advanced payments the difference between the two and how to operate with them:

        - **Advanced payments** - When the advanced payments are used the value of the advanced payments registered and used for the day are registered as revenue and hence they should be already processed with the rest of the revenue. The Advance payment charges are always with **revenue_group = deposit.** Newly received advanced payments are exposed as positive charges while the consumption of the advanced payments are negative charges;

        - **Deposits** - The deposits are handled as payments in open folios. Those payments may be registered in two types of folios:

            - **non-deposit folios** and you can collect the information about those payments using [<b>folio_ledger</b>&nbsp;](https://api-docs.clock-software.com/#c11a0f8b-b69b-47a2-951f-4f9229fbda31) for a given revenue date using **deposits_in_advance_from_non_deposit_folios** from **date** array.

            - **deposit folios** from the collected payments you can collect the folio where the payment is registered and check if the folios is a deposit one (deposit = true)

    - **Closed folios and issued invoices**. [<b>folios - VIEW LIST</b>](https://api-docs.clock-software.com/#cd53ffee-69f5-48ce-8d56-90a87f0a1c46) endpoint may be used to get the list of IDs of folios which have to be synchronised. The results may be [<b>filtered</b>](https://api-docs.clock-software.com/#using-parameters-for-data-filtering) so the list of IDs will contain only the ones which have to be synchronised. Information about every folio ID is fetched using [<b>folio - VIEW</b>](https://api-docs.clock-software.com/#29db4205-4bc0-4402-bdee-9af794558e1a) endpoint. Additionally you can add the [<b>document_type</b>](https://api-docs.clock-software.com/#ab384c3e-94c2-488b-9f5a-b16fa65a1551) in your filters if only certain document types are needed;

    - **Accounts Receivable.** It represents the money owed to the hotel by the clients who have received services or goods but have not yet and those are represented with invoices and the correction documents associated with invoices:

        - **Invoices** - Use [<b>folios</b>&nbsp;](https://api-docs.clock-software.com/#cd53ffee-69f5-48ce-8d56-90a87f0a1c46)  endpoint to get the list of folios filtered with **payed=false&close_date=current_date(yyyy-mm-dd format)** parameters. The result will contain closed folios which are not paid and are forming the accounts receivable. Once you start collecting the details for the individual folios you need contragent_billing_info to identify the customer. To calculate the amount subtract the [<b>payments&nbsp;</b>](https://api-docs.clock-software.com/#a46c412e-27e7-4a1f-8d96-dedaf579a391) registered for the folio from the folio value. Of course, you can pull all other details needed for the proper AR registration from the endpoint;

        - **Correction documents** - The list of correction documents for a given date may be easily collected using [<b>folios</b>](https://api-docs.clock-software.com/#cd53ffee-69f5-48ce-8d56-90a87f0a1c46) endpoint with parameters **payed=false&close_date=current_date(yyyy-mm-dd format).** Once you start collecting the details for the individual folios you need **client_folio_id** to identify the folio_id the current folio is correcting as well as the folio value. Of course, you can pull all other details needed for the proper AR registration from the endpoint;

    - **Liabilities** - The liabilities are all charges which are not paid and charged to folios which are still open. The liabilities can be collected using [<b>folio_ledger</b>&nbsp;](https://api-docs.clock-software.com/#c11a0f8b-b69b-47a2-951f-4f9229fbda31) for a given revenue date using **debts_open_folios** from **date** array.

request.description:
Configure the respective activity provider in **Clock PMS+. Open > Settings > Actovity Providers** and create new provider from type **GENERIC**. Give the provider a name and define the activity buttons display names for the different Clock PMS+ screens (Booking, Event and MyBookingPortal). If your system provide SPA services define..."**Book a SPA**" instead of "**Book with system X**" so it will be more intuitive for the staff and guetss. Configure the URLs for request (new), update and cancel of activity. The configured URL will be loaded in an iFrame so the staff member may complete the activity operation in your service where you can request all necessary details. Please the following parameters may be added in the URL configurations for better process handling:

- **%{activity_provider}** - will add the uuid of the activity to be used with [activity ](https://api-docs.clock-software.com/#847a3d5e-698d-4011-b925-5efd05c3ab2e) andpoints;

- **%{provider_uuid}** - the provider uuid will be added to the URL to be used with [activity_providers ](https://api-docs.clock-software.com/#1dfbed9d-d7e5-4601-b5ea-094f51446997) andpoint;

- **%{booking_number}** - the booking number will be added so you can search for the related booking usig [bookings ](https://api-docs.clock-software.com/#9e0b1e15-bfa7-46f8-bd08-811c6521966e) endpoint;

- **%{event_number}** - the event number will be added so you can search for the related event usig [events ](https://api-docs.clock-software.com/#22376bbf-a2b2-415a-b1ba-4b6444a25366) endpoint

- **%{reference_id}** - the reference_id updated when the acivity was completed will be added so the related records in your system may be easier identified;

- **%{cancel_reference_id}** - the cancel_reference_id will be added to the URL for a reference with your system.

